Anonymous Thu 22 Aug 2024 01:40:27 No.68472747 Report
Quoted By: >>68472827
>>68472472
Honestly you can cheat a little and have the setup within the story description or, at notes at the top of the story. That way the reader gets the gist even if the original story isn't read. I've got 3 stories set in the same universe with all different characters so far that aren't sequels, and that's how I've been doing it. So far, nobodys commented on being confused on what's going on.
For systems and terms, you can truncate those kinds of explanations in a way that's not too distracting. You can even put it bluntly and have (brief explanation or direct translation) in parentheses the first time it appears and just move on. The reader will get it.
Hope this helps!

Anonymous Thu 22 Aug 2024 01:52:42 No.68473045 Report
Quoted By: >>68473868

>Question for writefags: when you do a second story in a universe following different characters from the first, how much rehashing of lore should be added?
I treated Broken Sanctuary as its own story and presented everything as if it was fresh, even if you'll see that stuff in other stories. I did this because Venka, as a character, needs to be able to explain the world through her own eyes (and the narration surrounding her) rather than relying on the massive stack of stuff going on in the wider universe.

I won't do this for a second story featuring her. I'll pass out things that are relevant that the reader might know, but in a new and interesting way. I also won't step back and go, "hey, here's what's happening on the lizard tribe planet," in the story about a PTSD war vet murderhobo that doesn't even encounter any of their race until like the third book.

Anonymous Thu 22 Aug 2024 02:27:13 No.68473868 Report

>>68473045
I guess my worry isn't so much whether or not I convey the history of bumfucknowheresville, or the regulations of one group or another, so much as the character slang and the reasons behind their mannerisms.
The first story I wrote was pretty easy here, with the main character being the epitome of an average Joe, with most of the secondary characters explaining things to him as he encountered weird alien shit he had never heard of. This second story is sort of reversed, with the main character being experienced in the universe, while the secondary character is not really familiar with the world (while still being an alien and having her own lore to worry about). So when the experienced character talks to another experienced character, they'll use terms and have attitudes that would make sense if you've read the first story (ie: color coded roles in an organization) and have a prevalent attitude of disgust towards certain things that would seem cool to an outside observer (like getting violently angry at seeing a magic person use magic to do genuinely useful things).
I have some context in there, but I was just worried about whether lightly glossing over recurring details was good enough. I was pretty happy with how I did exposition the first time, and don't want to fumble it now.
